  "summary": "After watching a movie at the Athena Theatre in Tochi, Alexander Bonaparte Caste (ABC) reads a newspaper in the Princess Garden facing Tokei Harbor. The news reports the murder of Sir Charles Clarke in Chester, suggesting it is the work of a serial killer. The article links this crime to the murder of Elizabeth Barnard in Bexhill a month prior, noting that an ABC train timetable was found near Clarke's body. While reading, Mr. Cast is approached by a young man in a blue Eltex shirt who discusses the madness caused by war. Mr. Cast, appearing shaken and mentioning post-war headaches, causes the young man to leave in haste. As Mr. Cast walks toward town, he observes the public's intense speculation regarding the murder.\n\nThe murder of Sir Charles Clarke has caused a national sensation, turning the United Kingdom into an \"amateur detective army.\" The media, including the Daily Shine, has sensationalized the case, and Hercule Poirot has become a target of both public defense and journalistic harassment. Captain Hastings notes that newspapers often distort Poirot's words, but Poirot believes this media frenzy might cause the killer to underestimate him. While Scotland Yard and local police conduct exhaustive questioning of hotel managers and transport workers, Poirot remains focused on the psychology of the killer. He explains to Hastings that while the police focus on physical clues, he is building a psychological profile. Poirot predicts that another murder will almost certainly occur, and that the killer's next crime will reveal his true identity and nature.",
